    "poll": 43,
    "description": "This entry focuses on the people living in what is now the Punjab Province of Pakistan. Specifically, this entry focuses on the rural Punjabi village of Mohla, located in Gujrat District, between the time of 1947-1958. This time frame begins with the establishment of Pakistan in 1947 and ends prior to the substantial government changes of 1948. The principal ethnographic source for this society, Zekiye Suleyman Eglar (1960), selected Mohla because it was not greatly affected by the partition of India and the establishment of Pakistan, allowing for the study of traditional Punjabi culture. Most Punjabis are Muslim and follow Islam. However, religious beliefs and practices are not discussed in depth by the principal authority. Consequently, the present entry provides a general overview and is limited to the information that is available. Religious activities follow the Muslim calendar, which is tied to the cycle of the moon. Religious leaders include the village imam, whose role involves formalized rituals, and the pirs or spiritual leaders. Eglar (1960:71) states that “people know the fundamentals of their religion, which are so interwoven with their lives that they are a way of life to them.” The present entry considers the Punjabi religious group to be coterminous with the society itself.",
