    "description": "Jebel Barkal is an isolated sandstone butte beside the Nile, 23 km downstream from the mouth of the 4th cataract, near Karima, Sudan (N 18° 32.081, E 31° 49.876).  In ancient times it was called variously “Pure Mountain” and “Throne of the Two Lands” and was the chief landmark of a city called Napata, which marked the southern limit of Egypt’s African empire during the New Kingdom.  Perhaps even from prehistoric times, this hill was believed by the ancient Nubians to be the residence of a supreme Creator god and progenitor of kingship.  When the Egyptians conquered this region (known as “Kush”) about 1500 BC, they identified the god of the mountain as a primeval form of their own state god Amun of Karnak, whose chief sanctuary at Thebes lay 1260 km downstream.  \n\nFor centuries, the Egyptians had considered their king to be the son of Amun, and the Nile inundation to be his gift to Egypt. Since the Nile flood emanated from the distant South, they thus imagined that somewhere deep inside Kush, at or near the mysterious Nile sources, Amun had a primordial alter-ego, who released the waters each year, just as he had at the beginning of time.  It was this same primeval Amun whom they also believed dispensed the “royal ka,” the divine essence of kingship granted by the god to each new king, believed to be his own son.  When the Egyptians occupied Kush, they accepted Jebel Barkal as the place where this god dwelt.\n\nIf one gazes upon the hill today, it is easy to see why it acquired such revered status. Standing all alone in a vast desert plain, it was the perfect archetype of the legendary “Primeval Mound,” on which Creation was thought to have taken place. It faces the Nile with a sheer cliff, and from one corner rises a towering pinnacle, 75 m high, which, to ancient eyes, looked like a gigantic statue – but one in which different forms appeared, depending on the angle from which it was seen:  a) a colossal standing king, wearing the crown of Upper Egypt, b) an erect phallus, suggestive of Amun’s first creative act, and c) a rearing cobra (“uraeus”), suggesting both the presence of a mother goddess in serpent form and the symbol of kingship itself. By projecting all these forms, the pinnacle personified the primeval Amun himself (“Kamutef”), who was both male and female, embodied his own father and mother, and was able to generate and regenerate himself as his own child: the first divine king from whose body all others were thought to descend. \n\nAlthough Jebel Barkal was infrequently visited by the pharaohs, its sanctuary became the largest in Nubia.  As a coronation complex, it was thought to be a place where the king entered the mountain and ritually merged with the body of the god, his “father,” absorbing the “royal ka” and thus becoming a god-king himself.  \n\nWith the decline of the New Kingdom, the pharaohs were forced to retreat from Kush, which effectively cut their link to Jebel Barkal and their “father,” the primeval Amun, and severed their access to the “royal ka.”  As Egypt's kings weakened in this way, a native Nubian dynasty emerged at Napata, claiming to be Amun’s new “sons,” the exclusive possessors of the “royal ka,” and thus the only legitimate kings of Egypt.  By about 720 BCE these southern kings, in league with the Egyptian Amun priesthood at Thebes, seized control of Egypt and their family became the country’s 25th Dynasty.  \n\nAfter sixty years, the kings of Kush were expelled from Egypt by the invading Assyrians, but they returned to their homeland and established a kingdom in Sudan centered at Meroe that lasted another millennium.  Throughout most of that time Jebel Barkal remained the site of the chief cult center of their kingdom, where generations of their kings received their crowns from the god in the mountain and nearby which many built their pyramids.",
