    "description": "The Taizhou movement was initiated by a salt merchant, Wang Gen 王艮 (1483-1541), who came from Taizhou 泰州in today’s Jiangsu Province (North Zhili in the Ming). Wang Gen studied in a village school but dropped out after a few years due to poverty. He went to Shandong on business trips with his father. While visiting the Confucius temple in Confucius’ hometown Qufu, he had an enlightenment experience and became convinced that his own nature and the nature of the sage were identical.\n\nBack in Taizhou, Wang Gen created a centre, where people gathered for singing, meditation as well as a philosophical debate. We find both firewood gatherers and men with the highest examination degree in the movement. Whether women were part of it must wait for further research. After developing his own ideas independently, Wang Gen became a disciple of Wang Yangming (1472-1529) for a while. Therefore, the Taizhou movement is usually seen as part of the larger Wang Yangming movement.\nThe ideas and praxis of the Taizhou movement are heterogeneous. Wang Gen proclaimed the idea of self-respect inspiring many people in his time. This idea is probably one reason why people still are fascinated by Taizhou learning, both in the People's Republic of China, Taiwan, Japan, and Korea. The idea of self-respect questioned the traditional Confucian moral values of sacrificing yourself for your ruler and parents. The debates the Taizhou practitioners organized concerned moral questions, such as how to show solidarity with other people. Wang Gen argued that if you do not love and respect yourself, you cannot love and respect others. But he also talked about protecting yourself, which gives the impression that he already intended to create an organization that might be perceived as a threat to society and that their members therefore would need protection. Like many other Neo-Confucians, he was critical of the examination system. Wang Gen, however, went further and argued that learning which does not give you a feeling of joy is not true learning. He composed a song called “Joyous learning” (Lexue Ge 樂學歌), where joyous learning is celebrated. Wang Yangming said that the essence of one’s mind or heart (xin 心) is joyous. For the Taizhou practitioners, this meant to learn to know one’s mind and protect oneself. This was done by meditation exercises and social organization. Since the civil examination was of no help for learning to know oneself, Wang Gen forbade his sons to take part in the examinations.\n\nSome of the Taizhou practitioners were more moderate and others more radical. The discussion meetings are linked to the private academies, so free discussions might have started already in the Song dynasty (960-1279). In the Song, the academies were however strictly limited to the officials and people with examination degrees. AWang Yangming opened for spreading the message to simple men and women in the countryside, but it the Taizhou practitioners who realized it. With the Taizhou movement, commoners started to read and interpret the Confucian classics according to their own understanding, something which is similar to the Reformation when common men and women became religiously adult. The freedom of debate amont the Taizhou practitioners created a situation with different and contradicting ideas. Some could for instance argue against Buddhist rituals while others were very open to both Buddhist and Daoist ideas and praxis. As for their rituals, they were less hierarchical than the preceding Neo-Confucian. Rules for sitting, bowing and so on were also less strict.\n\nThanks to charismatic masters, the movement spread over China, from Taizhou in the East to Sichuan in the West, Hebei in the North and Guangdong in the South. Yan Jun 顏鈞 (1504-1596) and He Xinyin 何心隱 (1517-1579) made Jiangxi a new centre of the movement but also travelled around spreading the teachings. They confirmed desires, a step that was even more provocative than Wang Gen's idea of self-respect. Yan Jun established an “A hall for coming together in harmony” (Cuihe Hui 萃和會) and draw up rules for his community compact. He also led a seven-day meditation retreat, which includes breathing and meditation exercises with Daoist characteristics. He Xinyin’s “Society for collective harmony” (Juhe Tang 聚和堂) was something similar to Yan Jun’s society. It was a utopian society aimed at taking care of children, aged, and disabled members on a collective basis. The society organized schooling, capping ceremonies (a rite of passage for boys) and paid for funerals. They furthermore collected taxes within the society and delivered taxes to the authorities collectively. The Taizhou practitioners were famous for caring for their friends, and that applied especially to Yan Jun and He Xinyin. He Xinyin was accused of discarding the Confucian bonds between ruler and subject, father and son, elder and younger brother, husband and wife, only keeping the fifth bond between friends. Interestingly, the word they used for ’friend’,  tongzhi 同志, would later be chosen by the communists when translating the Western word “comrade” to Chinese. He Xinyin remonstrated when the local authorities imposed extra taxes on his community. This led to his arrest and imprisonment, but thanks to his friends he escaped and would change his name several times and travel from place to place lecturing wherever he went. It is at this time he took the name Xinyin 心隱 – the hidden heart.\nOur knowledge about the Taizhou practitioners comes to a large extent from Huang Zongxi’s 黃宗羲 (1610-1695) work The Records of Ming Scholars, which was published in 1693. Huang Zongxi was a Ming loyalist and a proponent of the Wang Yangming tradition. Accusations during the early Qing dynasty that Wang Yangming and his movement caused the fall of the Ming led Huang Zongxi to blame the radicals of the Taizhou movement such as Yan Jun and He Xinyin to save the more mainstream Wang Yangming followers. However, reading the work by Huang Zongxi carefully it is clear that he is not without admiration for the Taizhou practitioners. That the school of Wang Yangming would have caused the fall of the Ming dynasty seem to be very unlikely. It had probably to do with totally different reasons such as the military strengths of the Manchu invaders or other more practical issues. \nThe infamous thinker Li Zhi 李贄 (1527-1602) was inspired by the Taizhou message, but most Chinese and Western scholars do not regard him as a Taizhou practitioner. Li Zhi mentioned that He Xinyin was his teacher, but this was probably more in the sense of a spiritual teacher. Li Zhi has been called an arch-individualist and he was inspired by He Xinyin’s celebration of desires. However, Li Zhi also regarded Prime Minister Zhang Juzheng 張居正 (1525-1582) as his master, a person who was the opposite of He Xinyin as for ideals and way of life. The hatred between He Xinyin and Zhang Juzheng was mutual. Zhang might even have been the man who ordered the arrest and murder of He Xinyin. In 1579, the same year as He Xinyin was killed, Zhang Juzheng forbade the discussion meetings in the free academies, which was a heavy blow for the whole Wang Yangming movement. Li Zhi was deeply interested in Buddhism and left his family to live in a monastery. His eccentric lifestyle and provocative writings (especially his books \"A book to hide\" and \"A book to burn\") made him a target of harsh criticism. He was imprisoned and accused of immoral behaviour and seduction of people’s minds. The sources mention that he committed suicide in prison in 1602, but there are divergent narratives of this suicide already in the Ming dynasty (1368-1644) and, therefore, how Li Zhi died cannot be verified. Something which however is clear is that this kind of religious movement created great fear among men of power.",
