    "description": "Fuzi is the major work of Fu Xuan 傅玄 (217-278), an influential official and prolific writer of Wei-Jin times. This work has been listed among the miscellaneous treatises; considering that its core thoughts are Confucian, however, there is still controversy regarding the category of Fuzi. Most parts of Fuzi were written as political advice for Sima Zhao (211-265), posthumously the Emperor Wen of Jin, on how to establish a new regime and manage potential issues such as avoiding riots and selecting talents. This writing purpose to some extent explains why it is hard to categorize Fuzi, as Fu Xuan borrowed and integrated many schools’ ideas that were valuable to statecraft, such as legalist law and order, Mohist economical style, Confucian morality and education. Thus, Jordon Paper has claimed that Fu Xuan is “Confucian in theory, semi-Legalist in application of theory.” Regardless which school he belongs to, Fu Xuan proposed several insightful strategies on statecraft. For example, his innovative tax policy combined three principles: fairness, economy, and regularity. He opposed Xuanxue’s specious style and promoted trustworthiness and honesty. He suggested banishing the death penalty to save labourers. He also advocated personal cultivation and virtue (de 德) for rulers and officials. Fu Xuan’s strategies and proposals on statecraft have been valued and applied by later scholars and politicians, which can be seen through their efforts to preserve the Fuzi.\n\tAccording to the Jinshu, the Fuzi originally had inner, middle, and outer sections, which included four categories and six records, totaling one hundred and forty pieces, on the following themes: statecrafts, history, and current affairs. The book itself was quite lengthy: it had  several hundred thousand characters and was about one hundred juan long. During the Tang dynasty, the Fuzi was still complete; after the Song, it started to disappear and by Ming times, there was no record of it. \n\tDuring the Qing Dynasty, scholars produced several reconstructed editions of Fuzi. One of these is the Wuyingdian version (Wuying dian juzhen ben 武英殿聚珍本), compiled in 1774, which includes twenty-four sections mainly based on the Yonglu dadian 永樂大典, and forty-eight items (tiao 條) in a supplement. This edition was reproduced in the Siku quanshu huiyao 四庫全書薈要 and the Siku quanshu 四庫全書. Yan Kejun 嚴 可 均 (1762-1843) produced a four juan edition of the Fuzi in his Quan Shanggu saidai Qin Han Sanguo Liuchao wen. In Zhihai 指海, in 1843, Qian Xizuo 錢熙祚 formed a three juan edition of Fuzi. This edition is virtually copied in Ye Dehui's 葉德 輝 (1864-1927) Guangu tang suo zhushu 觀古堂所著書. In 1876, Fang Junshi 方濬師 (1830-1889) compiled the Fu Chungu ji: Fu Fuzi Jiaokan ji 傅鶉觚集 : 附傅子校勘記 in five juan. The first two juan and the supplement are about the Fuzi. \nFuzi has been highly regarded in history. Wang Chen 王沈 (d. 266) who, like Fu Xuan, once worked on the Wei shu 魏書 (which became part of the Sanguo zhi 三國志), held the post of Minister of Works 司空, a leading position for those who excelled in literature. Commenting on the Fuzi he said, \"Examining the book that you [Fu Xuan] have written, Sir, [I find] that your expressions are well reasoned and useful, provide good policies, and preserve and revere the Confucian teachings. They are capable of thwarting the propagation of the philosophies of Yang [Zhu 楊朱] and Mo [Di 墨翟] and equal the philosophies of Xun [Zi 荀子] and Mencius of past generations.\"  During the Tang Dynasty, the prominent official and historian, Wei Zheng 魏徵 (580-643), confirmed the Confucian values of Fuzi by selecting some of its chapters about government and politics for inclusion in his book Qunshu zhiyao 群書治要. The editors of the Siku quanshu 四庫全書 regarded the Fuzi as a Confucian work and acclaimed it in their Zongmu tiyao 總目提要: \"[The extant works of Jin’s philosophers consist of only Fu Xuan’s book; all of its discussions concern governing principles and explain Confucian teachings. [His] ingenious intentions and excellent speeches are everywhere. Thus, [I] believe both Lunheng and Changyan are inferior to this book. The book [contains] incomplete chapters and broken slips volumes. If we gather together its extant pieces, we still can examine and discover one-tenth [of its meanings]. This is indeed valuable.”",
