    "description": "The Amduat is a pictorial–textual composition which describes the nocturnal voyage of the sun-god and his entourage through the subterranean underworld, where he unites with the underworld god Osiris (representing an \"engendering principle\") and is rejuvenated before being reborn from the eastern horizon at dawn, re-enacting the original moment of cosmic creation.\n\nThe original title of the composition was the \"Writing/Drawing of the Hidden Space\". The common scholarly designation \"Amduat\" renders the generic Egyptian term \"scroll of that which is in the underworld\", which was assigned to later copies of this and several other compositions.\n\nThe tomb of Thutmose III (KV 34 in the Valley of the Kings in ancient Thebes, on the west bank of the Nile near modern Luxor) contains the earliest extant full copy of the composition in all three of its versions: a \"long\" version that combines descriptive text with images of entities inhabiting the underworld; a \"short\" version, without images, which summarizes the events of each hour; and a tabular \"catalogue\" (also termed an \"index\") of captioned figures appearing in the long version. The tomb of Thutmose III provides the only known example of the catalogue.\n\nIn the tomb of Thutmose III, the \"long\" and \"short\" versions of the Amduat are inscribed on the walls of the oval burial chamber in the tomb. The \"catalogue\" is inscribed on the walls of the antechamber leading to the burial chamber.\n\nThe \"long\" and \"short\" versions are divided into 12 sections, each describing (and depicting, in the case of the \"long\" version) the activities of the sun-god and his interactions with various underworld inhabitants in a region of the underworld. One region is traversed in each hour of the night between sunset and sunrise.\n\nThe Amduat is part of a broader category of cosmographic compositions termed \"underworld books\" or \"netherworld books\". Other members of this category include the Book of Gates, Book of Caverns, Books of the Earth, and the Enigmatic Books of the Solar-Osirian Unity. Closely related compositions are the cosmographic Book of the Day, Book of the Night, Book of Nut (also known as the Blueprint of the Course of the Stars), and the non-cosmographic Book of Adoring Re in the West (also known as the Litany of Re). Complementing these was a composition now termed the \"cult-theological treatise\" or \"king as sun-priest\" text, which has a similar focus on esoteric religious knowledge. All these compositions are known mainly from New Kingdom sources (mid- to late 2nd millennium BCE), with later copies from the 1st millennium BCE; some of them, such as the Amduat, Litany of Re, and cult-theological treatise, may have originated in the Middle Kingdom (early to mid-2nd millennium BCE), although the topic of dating continues to be debated.\n\nAlmost all New Kingdom copies of the Amduat come from royal tombs. The only known non-royal example is from the tomb of the vizier (highest-ranking administrative official in the Egyptian government) Useramun, who served under Thutmose III. Access to and circulation of the composition and/or its content remains debated. It likely originated in initiatory rituals for a restricted group, before being secondarily deployed in tombs due to its solar themes, which fit with intensive developments in solar theology (including hymns and ritual texts) and its mortuary significance during the early New Kingdom.",
