    "description": "Tutankhamun reigned as king of Egypt from about 1334-1325 BCE, in what has come to be referred to by scholars as the 18th Dynasty of the New Kingdom. Tutankhamun seems to have died unexpectedly, and the cause of his death has received significant speculation. While this king is one of the most famous individuals from the long history of ancient Egypt, it is not due to fantastic feats or accomplishments. Indeed, Tutankhamun did not reign very long and accomplished relatively little. He is famous instead, because of his tomb. His tomb is the only well preserved, (mostly) intact royal tomb from ancient Egypt. It is located in the Valley of the Kings in Thebes. Discovered by Howard Carter in 1922, this tomb was filled with an incredibly rich hoard of treasure. It was given the designation \"KV 62\" as tomb number 62 in the King's Valley. The tomb and its treasures, while also serving as examples of the abilities of Egypt's skilled craftspeople and artists, also provide extensive information about religious beliefs and practices during this era.",
