    "poll": 43,
    "description": "‘Beat Buddhism’ refers to the intermediary period of experimentation with Buddhism by members of the Beat Generation (1944-1960s), most notably Jack Kerouac, Allen Ginsberg, and Gary Snyder, that preceded the emergence of popular institutional forms of convert communities in the United States which maintained religious and secular spaces for practice, like temples or meditation centers. Rather, the location of a uniquely Beat praxis of Buddhism originates from a literary tradition of exploration into ‘Oriental’ religions and mysticism first made possible by the American Romantic lineages of Transcendentalism and Theosophy in the 19th century. Although wrought with colonial assumptions about Asia; Transcendentalist writers, like Ralph Waldo Emerson and Henry David Thoreau, heavily influenced the Beats’ idealistic reinterpretation and socially-informed deployment of Buddhism, which attracted the attention of mainstream American readers for the first time in the Fifties. \nThe Beat Generation from which the distinctly Romantic, Protestant, and subterranean nature of Beat Buddhism arises, represents a subcultural movement that marks a watershed moment in the advancement of postmodernism in post-World War II America. The central elements of the Beat’s countercultural movement included the rejection of a status-quo maintained by traditional Christian values, a rejection of economic materialism, and a rejection of the stratification of classes based on socio-economic conformity. Instead, they sought out alternative American and Asian spiritual traditions on a quest for sexual liberation and human transcendence. In their radical pursuit of ‘satori’ (sudden enlightenment), a sudden experience of reality unfettered by the illusory restraints of dualism that appeared on the American landscape in the form of inequitable social norms, Beat Buddhism extends the discourse of D.T. Suzuki and Alan Watt’s, who repackaged Japanese Zen for American audiences by emphasizing the pure experience of the emptiness, or nondualism, of reality through the practice of living spontaneously. \nDespite the non-institutional (or even anti-institutional) and transient foundation of Beat Buddhism as a religious interlocutor between the Orientalist exploration of Buddhism through the early-20th century, and the birth of convert communities in the United States; it contains several elements that can be identified as core beliefs and practices. First, Beat Buddhism is primarily concerned with the Four Noble Truths and how to overcome individual suffering within one’s current life. For Beats like Kerouac, Buddhism provided an ontology that explained suffering as the result of social ignorance and unrest. Second, drawing from Suzuki and Watts, Beat Buddhism is emphatically centered on experiencing what Kerouac coined “the golden eternity” or emptiness as a means of escape. Beat Buddhists believed that by training oneself to perform spontaneous acts of artistic expression, especially through “stream of consciousness” prose and poetry, one could experience their true (non) selves, unadulterated by the social baggage of 1950’s America. \nThird, in a shortlist of main elements that characterize the Beats’ mobilization of Buddhism, is their romanticism of the mendicant or ascetic lifestyle. Phrases like “Zen-lunatics” and “rucksack revolution;” and hermit-like livelihoods requiring immersion with nature, like train-hopping, logging, sailing, and serving posts on fire lookouts, are idolized in the pages of Beat literature. Thus, Beat Buddhism, the quintessential form of American Buddhism from the Fifties and Sixties, maintains its lineage of textuality in which American Transcendentalism and Buddhism modernism intersect in a mutual clarion-call to rebel against the suffering caused by social conformism.",
