    "description": "The personal Prelature of the Holy Cross and Opus Dei, usually just called Opus Dei  (\"Work of God\" in Latin), is a Roman Catholic, international institution which proclaims that lay people (i.e. non priests, monks, and nuns) can and ought to seek holiness in their ordinary life in the world. It was founded by St. Josemaria Escriva, a Spanish priest who lived from 1902-1975, and was declared a saint by the Catholic Church in 2002. According to St. Josemaria, on October 2, 1928, he saw by divine inspiration that God was asking him to spread the universal call to holiness, and that a new path would be opened up within the Church – Opus Dei – to spread this call throughout the world. Since its founding, Opus Dei has welcomed and spiritually motivated people of every racial, social, and secular condition. There are now around 90,000 members of Opus Dei, and its message has reached millions. \nOpus Dei is not a religious order of the Catholic church, nor is it a third order, i.e. an extension of a religious order made up of lay people attracted by the order’s spirituality. Members of Opus Dei often draw a comparison between their lives and the lives of the early Christians. The early Christians lived out their baptismal call seriously, seeing work, family life, and the ordinary events of each day as opportunities for drawing close to Christ, and making him known to others. Externally they did nothing to distinguish themselves from their fellow citizens. Likewise, the members of Opus Dei are ordinary people. They work like everyone else and live in the midst of the world just as they did before they joined. This distinguishes Opus Dei from the religious orders of the Catholic Church. Nor did Opus Dei arise to bring a solution to the situation in a given country at a given time. Rather, it claims to possess a universal spirit for all times and all centuries.  Visibly and in fact, Opus Dei aims to form contemplatives in the middle of the world rather than outside of it. The ideal is to live Christianity in the context of earthly occupations. The patron of Opus Dei is St. Joseph, who combined prayer, ordinary work, and family and social life in a continuous symbiosis, making it impossible for these to be separated from one another.  \nWhile the spirituality of Opus Dei emphasizes the pursuit of holiness in work and the ordinary events of daily life, its foundation is an awareness of every human being’s divine filiation, or identity as a child of God. Opus Dei seeks to foster among Christians a deep awareness of their being children of God, which includes confidence in divine providence, simplicity in their dialogue with God, a need for fraternity among all people and respect for human dignity, a truly Christian love for the world and all realities created by God, and a spirit of peace and cheerful hope. Other key features of Opus Dei’s spirituality are the importance of prayer and sacrifice, the value of personal freedom, charity towards others, and unity of life (i.e. the integration of one’s interior and religious life with one’s professional, social, and family life).",
