    "description": "The Adi Dravida movement was an early-20th century Tamil Paraiyar-caste [Dalit] Buddhist community founded by the Tamil thinker-activist Iyothee Thass (1845-1914) and overseen by his organization, the Dravida Mahajana Sabha, during Thass's lifetime. Valluva Sakya Buddhism, the label by which Thass sought recognition for the Adi Dravida movement in the broader Buddhist world, was founded on a reading of Tamil history that positioned the Paraiyar caste, and specifically the Valluva Sakya subgroup of Paraiyars identified as descendents of Śakyamuni Buddha himself, as a class of religious specialists in a pre-Sanskritic [i.e., Dravidian], Tamil Buddhist society. Consonant with important cultural and intellectual trends in the early-modern Tamil country, which focused on the non-Sanskritic roots of ancient Tamil civilization, Thass's Adi Dravida movement was the first movement in the Tamil country to connect a Dravidian-focused reading of Tamil sociocultural history to a discrete program of caste reform and Paraiyar community activism, the hub of which was Thass's newspaper, \"(Oru Paisa) Tamiḻaṉ\" (\"One Paisa Tamilian\").  While at its peak the Adi Dravida movement boasted bustling communities in the Tamil country, Ceylon, Burma, and South Africa, Thass's death in 1914 led to the gradual decline of the Adi Dravida movement, and by the late 1920s most of the Adi Dravida activist community had adopted the rationalist-atheist Dravidianist model of anti-caste activism associated with E.V. \"Periyar\" Ramasamy's Self-Respect Movement (suyamariyātai iyakkam). Although Thass's Adi Dravida Buddhism is no longer a major active community tradition, its influence can be observed in several realms of modern Tamil public society. First, the term \"adi dravida\", originally popularized by Thass's movement and taken up in E.V. Ramasamy's Self-Respect Movement, became an official Tamil Nadu state government designation for Scheduled Caste communities, and remains a common label for these groups in present-day Tamil Nadu. Second, the surge of interest in recovering Dalit histories associated with Subaltern Studies and the formation of radical Dalit social activist groups in the latter half of the 20th century, in particular Tholkappiyan Thirumavalavan's Viduthalai Ciruthaigal Katchi (\"Liberation Panthers Party\"), a Tamil Dalit political party that follows Thass and Periyar in connecting the project of Dalit liberation with the project of Tamil cultural regeneration through the de-Sanskritization of Tamil society.",
