    "description": "Amdo is a vast region on the Sino-Tibetan borderlands, which includes parts of Kokonor, South Gansu, and North Sichuan. Amdo is occupied by diverse communities, including Tibetan, Mongol, Monguor, Chinese and Turkic Muslims, etc. In the thirteenth century, Tibetan Buddhism developed thrivingly in Amdo during the reign of the Mongol Empire. As the middle ground between Tibet and China, Amdo became a critical cultural nexus of diverse cultures. In this context, Tsongkhapa, the Geluk School's founder, was born in Amdo. Starting from the fourteenth century, the Geluk School spread widely in Amdo. Because of the Khoshut Mongols' patronage after the late sixteenth century, the Gelukpa power rose promptly in Amdo. From the seventeenth to the eighteenth century, the development of the Gelukpa power in Amdo was directly related to the geopolitical policy of the Qing dynasty. Along with the Manchus and Mongols' patronage, the center of Amdo Gelukpas gradually moved from South Gansu to Kokonor. This significant phenomenon about Amdo Gelukpas was related to the westward movement of the Qing frontier policy. The development of the Gelukpa power in Amdo has several characteristics. Many Geluk monasteries took over institutional and religious legacies from other religious sects in Amdo, especially from the Sakya School. Along with the expansion of the Gelukpas in Amdo after the fifteenth century, many Amdo Buddhist communities converted to the Geluk School; however, they still preserved some original traditions and social practices in the pre-Geluk period. One of the most significant traits is the close connection between the Buddhist reincarnation system and local aristocratic power. It is widely known that the Sakya School's inheritance system is mainly based on kinship, especially the relationship between uncle and nephew. Because of the Mongol Empire's sponsorship, many Sakyapa priests and followers moved to Amdo and promptly dominated the region. After that, they established powerful local clans and monastic communities by practicing inheriting the Sakya School's lineage. In so doing, either monastic priests or local governors in the region were usually chosen from those families affiliated with the Sakya School. As both patrons and priests shared the same lineage, the political and religious powers tied together closely in Amdo. After these families gradually converted to the Geluk School after the fifteenth century, they still followed the inheritance system based on the patron-priest concept of the Sakya tradition, in which kinship played a critical role (See: Kung, 2018.). This unique phenomenon of the unity of politics and religion based on kinship profoundly influenced the historical development of Amdo Gelukpas until the early twentieth century. For instance, the Tenth Panchen Lama also held the Sakya lineage of the Khön Family.",
