    "description": "A survey of Britain south of the future region of Hadrian's Wall from 55 B.C.E. to 286 C.E. Created by Sharon Paice Macleod. Sharon Paice Macleod is a Canadian Celticist, grant-funded researcher, author, teacher, and professional Celtic vocalist and musician. She was a Young Apprentice of the National Symphony Orchestra, and her undergraduate work was in Music Performance at Ithaca College and Berklee College of Music. She then trained in Celtic Studies through the Department of Celtic Languages and Literatures at Harvard University, and has since taught Celtic literature, culture, religion, mythology and folklore at Smith College and University of Massachusetts (Extension). In addition to numerous journal articles, her published works include 'Celtic Myth and Religion: A Study of Traditional Belief,' 'Celtic Cosmology and the Otherworld,' a contribution to 'Celtic Myth in the 21st Century: The Gods and their Stories in a Global Perspective' (University of Wales Press), and the forthcoming 'Early Celtic Poetry and Wisdom Texts.' Ms. Macleod has given honorarium presentations at Wellesley College, University College Cork, and the Ford Foundation Lecture Series, and is the Director of the Eólas ar Senchais Research Project, examining early Celtic instrumental music and vocal art forms in socio-religious context.\nIntroductory remarks: The dates for this timeframe extend from Caesar's raids on south-east Britain in 55 and 54 BCE through much of the Roman occupation of Britain, which was punctuated by a decade of British independence between 286 - 296 CE. In this era, we see the introduction of Roman military power and the gradual conquest of Britain. Aspects of Roman culture and religion are increasingly visible, and generally accessible to members of native British tribes. This was particularly the case in areas where British rule and administration were unavoidable or uncontested, and/or where tribes allied themselves with the Roman presence for benefits of trade and material culture, as well as military protection. Not all tribes participated to a high degree, however, and as a result we see varying zones of Romanization or assimilation. \nThe situation on the ground was varied and complex. Some British tribe offered little or no resistance, many of whom were located in the south-east of Britain (Corieltauvi, Catuvellauni, Dubunni, Atrebates, Cantiaci, Regni) as well as the Demetae in south-west Wales and the Dumnonii in the south-west peninsula. Hostile tribes offered strong opposition and revolt, some of which took the Romans many years to overcome (sometimes only containing rather conquering them); these included three tribes in Wales (Deceangli, Orovices, Silures) and the Durotriges in the south of Britain. More mixed responses and interactions, including very large military campaigns, involved the varied smaller tribes in the federations of the Brigantes, the Iceni and the Belgae.\nSome tribes remained hostile to Rome and only participated as much as was necessary to preserve their territory and population. As a result, for the sake of this query, we must envision zones where Romanization was accepted and zones where it had less or little effect. Therefore, the data provided below will include answers and notes that apply to tribes whose religion continued on as before (as much as was possible), mixed areas of influence, and areas of higher Roman influence. During this era we also see the beginning of the slow and gradual introduction of Christianity into the region, possibly in the third century and definitely by the fourth centuries, by way of contact with traders and artisans arriving from other regions. Christianity was one of several religions introduced to Britain from the eastern part of the region, including those dedicated to the veneration of deities like Cybele, Isis and Mithras. For much of this era, Christianity would have been a minority religion amongst the native British; the rate of Christianization amongst Romans would have been higher (although Roman paganism and syncretic Romano-Celtic paganism would have been present throughout). Christianity experienced a slow and steady growth in the Empire throughout the 3rd century, and was decriminalized in 260 CE. The presence of these religious groups and practices are marked (prior to presentation of data) as follows: NB [Native British Practices, as seen in the First Timeframe], RC [Mixed / Syncretic Romano-Celtic practices], and RP [Roman or Romanized practices]. There will also be reference to minority religions such as Mystery religions of eastern origin involving the veneration of Cybele, Isis and Mithras [ER], as well as early Christianity [EC].",
