    "description": "A survey of Britain south of the future region of Hadrian's Wall from 500-55 B.C.E. Created by Sharon Paice Macleod. Sharon Paice Macleod is a Canadian Celticist, grant-funded researcher, author, teacher, and professional Celtic vocalist and musician. She was a Young Apprentice of the National Symphony Orchestra, and her undergraduate work was in Music Performance at Ithaca College and Berklee College of Music. She then trained in Celtic Studies through the Department of Celtic Languages and Literatures at Harvard University, and has since taught Celtic literature, culture, religion, mythology and folklore at Smith College and University of Massachusetts (Extension). In addition to numerous journal articles, her published works include 'Celtic Myth and Religion: A Study of Traditional Belief,'  'Celtic Cosmology and the Otherworld,' a contribution to 'Celtic Myth in the 21st Century: The Gods and their Stories in a Global Perspective' (University of Wales Press), and the forthcoming 'Early Celtic Poetry and Wisdom Texts.' Ms. Macleod has given honorarium presentations at Wellesley College, University College Cork, and the Ford Foundation Lecture Series, and is the Director of the Eólas ar Senchais Research Project, examining early Celtic instrumental music and vocal art forms in socio-religious context.\nIntroductory remarks: The culture and religion of Iron Age Britain displays many similarities with other Celtic-speaking regions, including northern Britain, Gaul, Ireland, Celtiberia, Galatia, and Celtic-speaking regions of Continental Iron Age Europe. These similarities - as well as divergent beliefs and practices - were widely remarked upon by numerous Classical authors. In this timeframe, similarities in culture and religion were commented upon by Julius Caesar in De Bello Gallico (V, 14 and VI, 13) during his raids on southern Britain in 55 and 54 BCE; as well as by Strabo in his Geographica (IV, 5, 2) c. 23 BCE and other commentators. Primary evidence will be drawn from archaeology in Britain and Classical accounts, with useful comparative materials from related cultural regions given above. In addition to the many print sources given below, the bibliographies of each of these resource will provide researchers with ample additional books and journal articles on specific topics.",
