    "description": "A survey of Augustinian/Roman Christianity in the British Isles from the years 600-800. Created by Phillip A. Bernhardt-House. Dr. Phillip A. Bernhardt-House is the History and Geography Department Chair at Skagit Valley College, and the Lead Faculty Member at Columbia College's Whidbey Island Campus, both in Washington state, U.S.A. A native of Washington, Phillip was educated at Sarah Lawrence College (Bronxville, NY, U.S.A.) with a junior year at Wadham College, Oxford University (Oxford, U.K.), obtaining a B.A. in medieval studies and creative writing with a minor in religious studies, at Gonzaga University (Spokane, WA, U.S.A.) for an M.A. in religious studies, and at University College Cork (Cork, Ireland) for a Ph.D. in Celtic Civilizations. Eir research interests include world religions, Irish mythology and speculative theology, Celtic mythology, comparative religion, ancient and medieval magic, werewolves, and gender and sexuality studies. A monograph called Werewolves, Magical Hounds and Dog-Headed Men in Celtic Literature was published in 2010 by The Edwin Mellen Press based on eir doctoral dissertation.. E also has articles appearing in journals and anthologies, including the Celtic Studies Association of North America Yearbook, Studia Celtica Fennica, the Canadian Journal of Irish Studies, and the Journal for the Academic Study of Magic, amongst others.",
