    "description": "Church of All Worlds (CAW) began April 7, 1962 at Westminster College in Fulton, Missouri, when two freshman psychology students shared a glass of water. Inspiration for this sharing of water came from a science fiction book they had both read: Stranger in a Strange Land by Robert Heinlein. In this book Valentine Michael Smith, a young human who was raised on Mars, experiences the ills our world and uses his training as a Martian to address them. In order to achieve this, he starts a church. That church was called the Church of All Worlds. These two college students, Lance Christie and Tim Zell (who now goes by Oberon Zell-Ravenheart), looked at this religion and thought “it was fiction so good is should be true,” and thus they engaged in the most holy of Martian traditions, water sharing. \n\nBy 1963 they had officially started the Church of All Worlds. Over the following five decades the group grew to have major influence on alternative religion in America. Adding to their science fiction roots they adopted aspects of the growing environmental movement, western esoterism, and human potential psychology. They found themselves at the center of a number of the social movements that the 1960s and 70s have become famous for. They coined the term polyamory. They were one of the first (or the first according to some sources) group to refer to themselves proudly as “pagan.”. They helped develop many of the rituals and traditions that would become the Neo-Pagan tradition. They fought a battle with the IRS to become one of the first tax-exempt organizations to identify as part of this tradition. They published the “Green Egg,” one of the most important Neo-Pagan magazines. The founders even raised living unicorns at one point. \n\nThe Church has also experienced many ups and downs. At its height in the late 90s, they numbered around 1200 due paying members, with many more coming their festivals, engaging in their rituals, and working alongside them in both their magazine, a number of store front locations and at ANNWN, their sacred land in Northern California. The Church still exists today though its membership is much smaller, with less than a hundred due paying members in the United States. Still, the group continues to attract new adherents, its founder, Oberon Zell, maintains a busy schedule of speaking engagements and writing projects. In 2004 Zell opened the Grey School of Wizardry, an online magick school self-consciously based on Hogwarts, from the Harry Potter novels. Showing that many still keep their science fiction roots close, remaining invested in a sense of play, creativity, and a keen eye for popular culture.",
