    "description": "Vasco-Aquitanian religion is documented primarily through the epigraphic remains of votive dedications, inscribed contractual obligations and gifts establishing a relationship with a deity, erected by private and public individuals in the central and western Roman Pyrenees and northern and southern foothills and hinterlands of the range. The bulk of these dedications to local deities occurred in the first two centuries CE. We cannot determine the contours of the priestly hierarchy or the religious institutions of Vasco-Aquitanian religion as  no recorded priests (sacerdotes, flamines, or local offices) are known epigraphically. There are differences between religious features among the Pyrenean Aquitani and the Vascones of Hispania Tarraconensis, but many similarities. The bulk of our evidence comes from the Pyrenees for this religious group. The greatest concentration of Vasco-Aquitanian deities occurs in the territory of the town of Lugdunum Convenarum (mod. Saint-Bertrand-de-Comminges). That town, said to be founded in 72 BCE by Pompey, features few Vasco-Aquitanian gods but primarily Roman deities. By contrast the hinterland of the town, where most of the industrial operations of the Convenae occurred, features the bulk of votive dedications to local deities with  Vasco-Aquitanian deities or Latin-named deities clearly masking local gods. Several of these deities, such as Fagus \"Beech Tree\", Sex Arbores \"The Six Trees\", Arixo (\"oak\", cf. Basque hartiz \"oak\"), Artehe (\"Holm Oak\", cf. Basque arte),  Leherennus (\"Pine\", cf. Basque leher), Erriapus (\"The Stone One\", cf. Basque harri \"stone\"), and Ageio are linked to sites of industry or traditional economic activities, such as silvopastoralism, pitch production, iron mining, and marble quarrying. There seems to be evidence of corporate worship of certain of these economic gods by individuals connected with large-scale industries, above all marble quarrying and iron mining. For example several collective dedications exist at or near the sites of work by those who seem to have been physically involved with that work: CIL XIII 1384 (Asque / Bigerriones): Ageio deo / pagani / Ferrarienses / ex voto \"To the god Ageio, the pagani Ferrarienses ('iron mining contract laborers' or 'residents of the iron-mining district') set this up to the god Ageio in fulfillment of a vow\", and  AE 1951, 233 (Saint-Beat / Lugdunum Convenarum): Deo / Erria/pe v(otum) s(olverunt) / marmo(rarii) / omnes \"All the marble workers fulfilled their vow to the god Erriapus.\" Some scholars have conflated such gods with \"natural worship\" in the past without connecting it to similar economic motivations underpinning votive usage elsewhere in the Roman world. The votive dedications of the Convenae and other populations in the Roman Pyrenees, as elsewhere in the Mediterranean, reveal deities closely linked to the lived realities of their dedicants. The beliefs about and the mythologies of these gods are beyond access to us but perhaps remain alive in elements of Basque folklore.",
