    "description": "Fangshi (方士) has been variously translated as technicians, masters of methods, recipes or esoterica, even necromancers. Historical records show that they were active through the period of the late Warring States to the Han. It is unlikely, however, that they had a collective identity as such, as scholar Nathan Sivin notes, “fangshi is not a social category but an epithet.” \nNo writings by these men which would represent their voice directly have been left. Instead the Shiji 史記 (Records of the Historian), written by Sima Qian司馬遷 (c.145-c.86 BC) offers the most famous and earliest accounts of the fangshi. Overall described in a negative light, the historian tells us that they were hired to procure drugs of immortality—the first emperor of the Qin (r.247-210 BC) had a great desire to become a transcendent— and promised a way to ascend to Heaven through sacrificial offerings—the emperor Wu of the Han (r.140-87 BC) seems to have preferred this. \nTheir origin is obscure. According to the Shiji, they were mostly from the coastal areas of the Qi and Yan states. Evidence of their presence came to light in the invitation of the first emperor of the Qin upon the latter’s imperial tours after the unification. Since then, they rose to prominence at the court of the Han. However, historians and thinkers, especially of the Eastern Han (25-220 CE) were increasingly critical of these men saying that they were just selling empty words. Despite this disapproval, they became widely popular and some were revered as cult figures. From the 2nd century CE, many fangshi were entered in hagiographies of transcendents (xian 仙). \nFor this reason, it seems almost impossible to draw a clear boundary between historical and fictional accounts of these men. This makes it difficult to evaluate their historical importance to religious developments in China. Several questions remain to be answered: how much did their activities overlap with other technical specialists like physicians, astrologers and diviners? Did the yangsheng 養生 (nurturing life) practices—diet, drugs ingestion, gymnastics and breathing cultivation etc.—widely circulated during the Han originate from the methods of the fangshi? What is the relationship between this group and the transcendents found in early accounts like the Zhuangzi 莊子? Though often condemned or mysticized, it might be fairer to say that they occupied an intermediate position between those who strived for transcendence by cultivating their body and those in positions of power who sought immortality by occult recipes. Most significantly, they played a crucial role in shaping Daoist religious traditions of later periods as their methods and lineages were largely incorporated in the techniques and teachings of the Dao (daoshu 道術/daojiao 道敎).",
    "belongs_to_external_poll": false
