    "description": "Ganden Monastery was established in 1409 by Tsongkhapa Losang Drakpa (1357-1419), the founder of the Geluk tradition. At an altitude roughly 4075 meters above sea level, it is located some forty kilometers northeast of the city of Lhasa in the province of Ü in Central Tibet (today, the Chinese Dagzê District). Its full name is Drok Riwoché Ganden Nampar Gyelwé Ling, although it is also called Geden in accord with prophecies connecting its name to the syllable gé. Tibetan sources state that the term Geluk arose from the name Geden, with those at this monastery known as “upholders of the tradition of Geden” (dge ldan ring lugs ‘dzin pa). \n\nAccording to one prophecy, the monastery was conferred the name Ganden due to a prophecy that Tsongkhapa would be reborn in Tuṣita in his next life. Prophecies related to Ganden make up a major part of Tibetan historical accounts of the monastery, and describe elements such as its founder, location, certain sacred objects related to Ganden, and the qualities of its early hierarchs and their disciples. On a mundane level, Ganden was founded out of the consternation Tsongkhapa’s disciples had for their itinerant lifestyle, as well as concerns for Tsongkhapa’s well-being as he aged. \n\nDrok Ri or Nomad Mountain was chosen as the site of Ganden in accord with prophesies and divinations. It possesses numerous geomantic elements marking it as an auspicious abode; in particular, Ganden is famed for the presence of “self-arisen” forms, spontaneous natural phenomena that embody or evoke supernatural phenomena, as well as objects and events from the lives of Tsongkhapa and other influential figures. Situated along the circumambulation routes surrounding Ganden, these phenomena, along with Ganden’s major festivals, represent two of the monastery’s main attractions for lay devotees. \n\nDuring its phase of initial construction, Ganden consisted of a residence for Tsongkhapa, a general assembly-hall with a shrine, and living quarters for about seventy monks, with the foundations laid for one hundred more. Later, more structures were added, including Yangpachen Temple, a temple for Tsongkhapa's reliquary stupa, and buildings for the two main colleges of Ganden, Jangtsé and Shartsé. Also present are retreat-huts that belonged to Tsongkhapa and Khedrub Jé, and a printing house. All these structures contain numerous religious objects and murals. Perhaps the most sacred item is Tsongkhapa’s own reliquary stupa, which continues to attract devotees to the present day.",
