    "description": "A description of the British Isles after the Christianization of the Roman Empire. Created by Nicole Volmering. Nicole Volmering is a postdoctoral researcher specialising in the medieval religious literature and history of the insular world. Her research interests include monasticism, eschatology, martyrologies, and the history of the book. She holds a PhD in Early and Medieval Irish from University College Cork, which won the Johann Kaspar Zeuß prize, as well as a MA in English (track Old English). She is editor of the forthcoming Martyrologies in the Insular World. Context: The ‘British Isles’ in this document refers primarily to the area of Great Britain south of Hadrian’s wall.\nNote: The gradual Christianization of Britain in this period was not a homogeneous or coherent process. The British Church appears to have a well-integrated provincial hierarchy in the fourth century: our earliest documentary evidence is the presence of British bishops at the Council of Arles in 314 CE. Yet its continuation is shadowy until the sixth century. Christianity retained a stronger foothold in the Western and some northern parts, while it may have declined in the East under pressure of Germanic raids and settlements by the end of the period. Just across the northern border however the Picts also appear to adopted (and abandoned) Christianity, while St Patrick brought it across the water to Ireland. The “re-conversions” of Anglo-Saxon peoples belong to the sixth century.",
