    "description": "Gaul was a large region of Iron Age Europe inhabited by Celtic language speaking tribes. Encompassing 191,000 square miles, it included what would become France, Luxembourg and Belgium, and parts of Switzerland, northern Italy, the Netherlands and Germany (particularly the west bank of the Rhine).\n\nPrior to the Roman conquest in 51 BCE, the people of Gaul did not typically create written records of any size. As a result, much of our knowledge of the region is obtained through archaeology, including the names of tribal leaders and native imagery found on Gaulish coins. \n\nThis is augmented by detailed (but not always reliable) written accounts by Julius Caesar and other Classical commentators. In addition, useful comparisons pertaining to culture and religion have been made with other Celtic-speaking cultures in Britain, Ireland and Galatia (Asia Minor). \n\nPre-Roman Gaul consisted of a large number of tribes or chiefdoms whose economy was based on herding and agriculture, as well as trade. The religion of pre-Roman pagan Gaul consisted of polytheism, with the possibility of animism as well. Our main evidence includes archaeological data pertaining to the location, layout and orientation of ritual sites, votive offerings and depositions, and burial practices, as well as informed analysis of ethnographic accounts of Gaulish religion and belief, including the training and functions of the Druidic class of religious specialists. \n\nIn addition, some elements of Roman era epigraphy and iconography may shed light on native belief, particularly in regard to Gaulish gods and goddesses and their attributes. Linguistic analysis and comparisons of place-names, personal names, theonyms, and socio-religious terminology from other Celtic regions has proven fruitful, as has examination of possible parallels with religious themes and symbolism from early medieval Irish and British written sources. \n\nFrom the available evidence we can discern a vibrant culture in Gaul, whose people were described as wearing stunning brightly coloured clothing and many gold and bronze ornaments, and who were skilled metalworkers, horsemen, mariners and artisans. They valued truth, wisdom, honesty and courage, as well as music, eloquence, poetry and skill.\n\nAs in many traditional cultures, religion infused nearly every aspect of daily life, and recent archaeological work has focused on the interconnection between religious spaces and dwellings or settlements. There appear to have been numerous Gaulish deities, whose attributes were associated with aspects of culture (healing, prosperity, warfare, magic, horsemanship, food and drink, arts and fertility) as well as those whose names reflect aspects of the natural world (rivers, wells, trees, groves, animals and birds).\n \nReligious ceremonies were presided over by members of the highly-trained Druidic class, who also served in a judicial capacity. They were described as highly skilled arbitrators, moral and natural philosophers, and experts in the nature of (and communication with) the divine. The Druids appear to have also provided counsel to leaders, performed divination and engaged in healing rituals. \n\nThey served as instructors to druidic candidates over a period of many years, and this training involved an immense amount of memorization, as this was an oral culture. The Druids apparently taught the people that the soul was immortal and after death would enter another body, and that the people should \"honour the Gods, do no ill deed, and practice valour.\" \n\nIt is important to note that the historically documented training and practices of the Druids in Celtic-speaking regions of Iron Age Europe have little or nothing to do with modern Neo-Pagan druidism or druidry, which are recent occult-based, earth-honoring religions developed in the 19th and 20th centuries.",
