    "description": "Sо̄kо̄ji (桑港寺) is a Sōtō Zen Buddhist temple located in San Francisco's Japantown. Founded on 8 December 1934 by Reverend Isobe Hо̄sen (磯部峰仙), Sо̄kо̄ji is arguably one of the most historically significant Zen Buddhist institutions in the United States. In addition to serving the religious and cultural needs of the Japanese American community in the Bay Area for over 85 years, Sо̄kо̄ji is the point of origin for many Sōtō Zen lineages in the U.S. The temple’s original location, a former synagogue at 1881 Bush Street, was purchased in 1934 by Teruo Kasuga. Over the next two decades, Sо̄kо̄ji’s Japanese American congregation survived incarceration during World War II—at which time they continued to make payments on the temple building—and anti-Japanese racism post-war. In 1959, Suzuki Shunryū (鈴木俊隆) was appointed Sо̄kо̄ji’s sixth head priest. After gathering a large following of predominantly white and non-Japanese disciples, Suzuki resigned from his position in 1969 and founded the San Francisco Zen Center (Hosshinji 発心寺) and Tassajara Zen Mountain Center (Zenshinji 禅心寺). Many of Suzuki’s students have become Zen teachers in their own right, such as Reb Anderson, Jakusho Kwong, and Mel Weitsman. Sо̄kо̄ji has also been home to several associate priests (所属僧侶) who went on to train students of their own or become important voices for Zen in the U.S., including Katō Wako (加滕和光), Chino Kōbun (知野弘文), and Katagiri Dainin (片桐大忍). Katagiri in particular, who was assigned to assist Suzuki in the 1960s, founded the Minnesota Zen Meditation Center (Ganshōji 願生寺) in 1972 and was key propagating Sōtō Zen Buddhism in the American Midwest. In 1980, construction began on a new building for Sо̄kо̄ji at 1691 Laguna Street, which was completed in 1984 and has been its home since. Sо̄kо̄ji continues to be a valued institution in the Japantown community. It offers private services (weddings, funerals, memorials, etc.), monthly services, and annual services such as the Spring and Autumn Equinoxes (higan 彼岸), Hanamatsuri (花祭り), and Obon (お盆). Sо̄kо̄ji also hosts a martial arts school, sutra-copying classes, tea ceremony courses, and is an avid participant in Japantown’s annual Cherry Blossom Festival. Finally, Sо̄kо̄ji has an active zazenkai (座禅会) or zazen meditation group that meets several times a week and holds occasional multi-day practice intensives (sesshin 接心).",
