    "description": "In order to classify Tibetan Buddhism, genuine classification principles have to be applied, e.g. according to the monasteries in which certain schools of Tibetan Buddhism were established, or on the basis of the name of the master to whom a particular school of Tibetan Buddhism is attributed, or according to the preferred spiritual and cultural background of a particular master.\n\nThe school is named after the Sakya Buddhist monastery founded in 1073 by Khön Könchog Gyelpo (1034-1102), which is located in Sakya and was called Sakya Densa (sa skya gdan sa) or Sakya Gönpa (sa skya dgon pa) in Tibet.\n\nThe history and teachings of the Sa skya pa school are based on the following \"five greats\":\nKun dga' snyin po (1092-1158), whose studies were mainly devoted to the cycle around Hevajra, the tutelary deity of the Sa skya pa himself. \nBsod nams rtse mo (1142-1182) worked towards a systematic order and classification of tantric scriptures and also provided summaries of the teachings. \nRje btsun Grags pa rgyal mtshan (1147-1216) is the author of numerous works of tantric and dogmatic exegetic and even medical treatises. \nSa skya Pandita (1182-1231), based on the Pramāṇavārttika of Dharmakirti, turned his attention mainly to problems of dogmatics and logic; he was also interested in rhetoric. \nThe last in this series, 'Phags pa (1235-1280?), an extremely prolific writer who wrote all kinds of dogmatic, tantric and liturgical subjects, he also addressed numerous letters to Mongolian princes, in which he summarised the basic elements of the Buddhist teaching.",
    "belongs_to_external_poll": false
