    "description": "A description of the British Isles after falling under the control of the Roman Empire. Created by Nicole Volmering. Nicole Volmering is a postdoctoral researcher specialising in the medieval religious literature and history of the insular world. Her research interests include monasticism, eschatology, martyrologies, and the history of the book. She holds a PhD in Early and Medieval Irish from University College Cork, which won the Johann Kaspar Zeuß prize, as well as a MA in English (track Old English). She is editor of the forthcoming Martyrologies in the Insular World. Context: The ‘British Isles’ in this document refers primarily to the area of Great Britain south of Hadrian’s wall. Britain was officially part of the Roman Empire from 43 CE. While there is some continuation of pre-Roman practices, the gradual Romanization of social, economic and ritual practices means that a native/Roman antithesis is too simplistic for this period. In the absence of a (surviving) self-authored literature, much of what can be gleaned of religious beliefs in (especially the earlier part) of this period comes from Romano-British archaeology.",
