    "description": "A description of the British Isles before falling under the control of the Roman Empire. Created by Nicole Volmering. Nicole Volmering is a postdoctoral researcher specialising in the medieval religious literature and history of the insular world. Her research interests include monasticism, eschatology, martyrologies, and the history of the book. She holds a PhD in Early and Medieval Irish from University College Cork, which won the Johann Kaspar Zeuß prize, as well as a MA in English (track Old English). She is editor of the forthcoming Martyrologies in the Insular World.\n\nContext: The ‘British Isles’ in this document refers primarily to the area of Great Britain south of Hadrian’s wall. \nNote: Britain was officially part of the Roman Empire from 43 CE. Little can be said with certainty concerning the religious beliefs held before this date since the only written sources from the period referring to religious beliefs and practices on the islands are Roman (thus offering a foreign perspective) and the archaeological evidence is difficult to interpret with respect to belief systems. The period is often referred to as ‘Late Iron Age Britain’ or ‘Celtic Britain’, but the use of the term ‘Celtic’ is disputed as it is unclear to what extent we can speak of a pan-Celtic religion in this period, when the region itself shows many localized practices.",
