    "description": "This is a spectrum of religious practices that span more than a century. They frequently cross or transcend ethnonyms and national boundaries and are being described as \"Uyghur\" here as a matter of convenience. The people who undertook them in the specified time frame called themselves by a number of names, of which Uyghur is the most current. This entry concerns Islam in the southern part of what is now Xinjiang, China in roughly the years specified. Until the mid 20th century, the region was locally called Altishahr, and religious practice was similar to that farther west in Central Asia. The time frame itself is suggestive of the texts from which these practices can be reconstructed. The end date is suggestive of a set of government policies towards and crackdowns on traditional religious practices that have, as far as is possible to know, effectively been a death knell for traditional Islam in Xinjiang.",
