    "description": "Thai Bhikkhunis are an elite network of monastics within the institution of Theravada Buddhism. The first Thai Bhikkhuni, Dhammananda Bhikkhuni, ordained in Sri Lanka in 2003. Since then the Thai Bhikkhuni community has grown to about 100. There is a community in central Thailand, outside of Bangkok, led by Dhammananda Bhikkhuni, housed in a temple called Wat Songdhammakalyani. Another community, which is part of this network, is led by Bhikkhuni Nanthayani. Her centers are in the north, with Nirotharam located in Chom Tong, and Suttajit in Doi Saket, both within the province of Chiang Mai. The third branch of Nanthayani is international, with bhikkhunis speaking English from all over the world, located in Chiang Rai. The third group is in the South, Koh Yoh in Songkhla province, led by Bhikkhuni Dhammakamala. All of these network members have been ordained in Sri Lanka, and although they live in Thailand, are part of the Sri Lankan Buddhist community, or sangha. This is because full ordination as a Bhikkhuni is illegal both by the state and Buddhist religion in Thailand, since 1928. Because of their ordination experience, and delicate political and religious situation within Thailand, the bhikkhuni communities form a network and strategies to maintain themselves within this unstable and sometimes hostile environment. There are other bhikkhunis living in Thailand, but these are living in smaller groups than the three mentioned above.",
