    "description": "Between the years 1838 and 1917, approximately half a million Indians were brought to the Caribbean through the indentured labor trade, a system developed after the British abolished slavery to provide cheap labor on sugar plantations.  144,000 of those laborers were brought to the twin island of Trinidad and Tobago.  On the plantations, Indians worked to maintain their cultural and religious traditions.  They soon united their community, using a remembered Hinduism as a platform upon which they could carve out a separate space for themselves within the larger society. They established temples, religious schools and organizations, and modified their religious practices to suit the conditions of the Caribbean island.",
