    "poll": 43,
    "description": "This group consists of the Dikshitars who are the hereditary priests of the temple, the local devotees, and those pilgrims who identify as having a special affiliation with Nataraja (some of whom are foreign). While Nataraja and his consort Sivakamasundari are found in shrines all across Tamil Nadu this is the only major temple where they, in the form of processional deities (utsava murti), are the central focus of worship. The temple is linked to other saiva temples. However, those temples are Saiva Siddhanta temples following the prescriptions of Saiva Siddhanta texts. The Natraja temple  differentiates itself as a Vedic temple with a ritual handbook composed by Patanjali, one of the revered saints of the temple. This variant means of worship, the atypical central deity and the temple's historical connection to ancient kings and devotional literature creates a particular type of Nataraja worshipper who is similar to but different from other Saivas.",
