    "poll": 35,
    "description": "This entry covers the people known as Sarereiket and who speak the Sarereiket dialect. Most live along the Rereiket River (Siberut Island, Mentawai Archipelago, Indonesia), residing primarily, as of 2017, in the communities of Matotonan, Buttui, Ugai, Madobak (Madobag), and Rokdok (Rogdog), as well as the developing settlements between those villages and the region of Attabai. Some Sarereiket people have also moved into the settlements surrounding Muara Siberut, especially Muntei. Sarereiket people are closely affiliated with the people of Saibi and Silaoinan, who speak near-identical dialects.\n\nThe Sarereiket Mentawai live both in settlement villages (barasi) and in traditional longhouses (uma) or other residences in the forest. Those living in settlement villages are more likely to attend regular services of religions like Protestantism, Catholicism, and Islam, and they are more likely to enroll their children in school. Nevertheless, \"forest people\" and \"settlement people\" are not distinct groups: not only do families commonly keep residences both in the rainforest and in the settlement villages, but people who live in the forest typically have family members who live permanently in settlement villages. I thus treat them as a single religious group.",
