    "description": "The Nāth Sampradāya is a religious tradition constituted by castes of householders and by an ascetic order subdivided into twelve branches (panths). The members of these lineages are variously known as Nāth Yogīs or Kānphaṭā Yogīs (\"split ears\", from the practice of piercing the thick of the ears upon full initiation, a designation today considered derogatory). The figures celebrated by the Nāth yogīs as first gurus of the tradition, Matsyendranāth and Gorakhnāth, probably lived in the 9th and 12th century respectively, but the Nāth world coalesced into a distinctive order much later and the first references to an organized Nāth Sampradāya date to the beginning of the 17th century.\n\nThe purpose of this entry is to provide a few introductory bibliographical references on the main aspects of the tradition.",
