    "description": "Historically, Mapuche or \"people from the land\" was the term used to designate the Mapuche occupying the south-central area of the Chilean territory but now the term is used by all Mapuche. The terms \"Huilliche\" (people of the south), \"Pehuenche\" (piñon-eating people of the mountains), \"Lafquenche\" (people of the coast), and \"Picunche\" (people of the north) were used by the Mapuche to differentiate their regional areas. The term \"Promaucae\" (rebellious people) was given to the Mapuche by the Incas.\r\nAboriginally, the Mapuche occupied the region between the Río Choapa (32° S) and Chiloé Island (42°50' S). The majority of Mapuche live in the Chilean provinces of Arauco, Bío-Bío, Malleco, Cautín, Valdivia, Osorno, and Llanquihue between 37° and 40° S.",
