    "poll": 35,
    "description": "The Demeter Cult encompassed, within several annual rituals, a significant cross-section of society in Eleusis and Athens, then all Classical Greece, then throughout the Roman Empire. The most famous of these, the Eleusinian mysteries, included Greeks and (eventually) Greek-speaking foreigners; both men and women, slaves and free, children and adults. (Committing murder prevented participation.) These mysteries included initiates, initiated participants, and initiates who had attained a state of \"contemplation\" (Gr. epopteia). There existed \"greater\" and \"lesser\" mysteries; initiates of the latter were deemed worthy to witness the former (i.e. they became 'mystai').\n\nThe other great cult ritual at which Demeter stood center, the annual Thesmophoria, involved only women. This festival and ritual took place originally at Athens, and only women married to Athenian citizens were eligible to participate. \n\nIn earlier periods, the Demeter cult(s) existed on a smaller, more localized scale.",
    "belongs_to_external_poll": false
