    "description": "Currently over one million Buddhists from diverse ethnic backgrounds live in Bangladesh. Many of them share the same ethnicity and language with Bengali Muslims and Hindus. They have been living in rural villages mainly in the Chittagong Plain District Bangladesh. On the other hand, Kolkata, the capital city of West Bengal in India, has become home for the largest Chittagong Plain Buddhist population outside Bangladesh. As part of the South Asian Buddhist revival movement in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, a few Buddhist families from Chittagong settled in Kolkata. They established the Bauddha Dharmankur Sabha (Bengal Buddhist Association) in 1891. More Chittagong Plain Buddhists joined the association during the 1947 India-Pakistan partition as well as at the 1971 Bangladesh’s independence. Currently a significant number of Chittagong Plain Buddhists live in West Bengal as well as in neighbouring states i.e., Tripura, Assam and Meghalaya.",
